The Smart Hand Controller (SHC) Add-on

This OnStep add-on is a hand controller with display which can be used to setup and control OnStep.  It's an adaptation (and extension in some respects) of Charles Lemaire's excellent "Teen Astro" hand controller firmware that allows it's use with a stock OnStep system.  Nearly all features are supported so an SHC+OnStep is a stand-alone telescope controller capable of setup, alignment, and operation (gotos to stars, Messier/Herschel400 objects, the planets, etc.)

This is a wired device that plugs into any OnStep (Alpha branch) controller that has an ST4 port*.

There are currently two versions of the SHC, one based on the Teensy 3.2, and the other on the ESP32. 

*** NOTE: if the SHC is plugged into OnStep's ST4 port NO OTHER DEVICES may be connected to the port (using a 1 port to 2 port modular adapter for instance) at the same time. ***

*** NOTE: during firmware upload to the SHC you must use the Teensy3.2 micro-usb connection but you must never have the SHC connected to other hardware (OnStep) via the ST4 connection (or Serial3/etc.) at the same time. ***

*** NOTE: versions of the EasyPCB SHC prior to 1.10 may have incorrectly positioned and/or labeled VCC and Gnd pins on the display connector.  Examine the pcb to be sure those match up with your display.  ***

The Teensy 3.2 SHC PCB and Case

*** Its up to you to understand the design, connection, limitations, and use of this device and it's components, I accept no responsibility. ***

My EasyEDA PCB and 3D printable case for this makes for an easy to build controller.  I can finish one of these in a single evening including printing the case, all soldering, and assembly.  Some SMT soldering is required but that's been pretty easy in my experience (just be careful to position each button properly while soldering it's first contact.)  The exact display I used was this 1.3" white OLED (SH1106.)  Other parts used are shown in the EasyEDA BOM.  There are two button types listed one has a round post and the other square.  I used the round ones and my 3D printable caps (which I made from glow in the dark filament) fit these.  For the square post type push buttons these caps should work I think (they are the same as used for the Basic Hand Controller and see that device for more info.)  If you don't have the 3D printer you'll have to find a case of similar size and cut/drill to make the PCB fit (which I imagine will not be a trivial task!)

SHC EasyEDA PCB

SHC Case design and STL files

Misc notes:

  • Be sure the display connections match up with the SHC PCB and Schematic, the order of pins can vary depending on display manufacturer.  The PCB is designed for a pin order of Gnd, Vcc, SCL, and SDA.
  • The SHC PCB's provision for a 6P6C RJ12 jack (for ST4 interface pass-through) isn't supported yet and the part must also be omitted if using my 3D printable case design.
  • All components are soldered directly to the PCB (no socket headers.) 
  • Be careful to install the resistor packs, RP1 and RP2, in their correct orientation with pin 1 having a small box on the PCB silk-screen.  Pin 1 on the device has a small dot next to it.
  • The Teensy3.2 has pin headers soldered on and then gets soldered to the back of the PCB first.  I then cut off the excess pin length extending through the PCB front side with small diagonal cutters.

  • The OLED display is soldered on next so there's a 0.2" (5mm) gap between the display PCB and the SHC PCB.
  • When soldering the surface mount buttons be sure to solder the "Shift" button (U6, the center button) first since the [N] and [S] buttons will be in the way if they are soldered before it.

  • For the RJ12 6P6C modular jack/cord that connects this to OnStep's ST4 port  I used this one from Amazon.com (one end needs to be cut off and soldered to the SHC PCB, or better a Molex KK plug crimped on and that gets plugged into the SHC PCB mating connector (as I did - using needle nose pliers as the "crimping tool".)  Digikey has a coil cord that should work instead if you have the tool to crimp on the RJ12 connector: P/N A0762RC-ND.
  • The above cord exits from the bottom of the SHC and is held in place on the PCB using the four holes provided and two small nylon ties "zip strips".
  • A small piece of red acetate sheet covers the white OLED.
  • The screws are black oxide SS, #6-32 x 3/4 inch length from mcmaster.com

ESP32 SHC

The ESP32 SHC offers the same features as the Teensy 3.2 SHC, but is cheaper and more available for people worldwide. The ESP32 also has more storage, so theoretically, more catalogs can be added in the future.

Here are the full details on the ESP32 SHC including a video, and detailed installation instructions.

There is also a link there to where you can order a ready to build kit.

Installing the Platform

For the Teensy 3.2 SHC:

Before you can flash the firmware on your board (Teensy3.2,) you need to install the platform for the Arduino IDE.

So be sure you've downloaded and installed the Teensyduino package.

For the ESP32 SHC:

Install the ESP32 platform.

Flashing The SHC Firmware

The source code is inside the OnStep folder under the "addons/St4Serial/SmartHandController" sub-directory.

Now open the SmartHandController.ino file inside this folder. Check the "ST4SmartConfig.h" file to be sure you have the correct display device selected.  Other options allow flexible configuration but shouldn't be changed for use with my EasyEDA SHC PCB.

Next, you'll need to add the U8g2 library and the Ephemeris to your Arduino libraries:

* You can download U8g2 from https://github.com/olikraus/u8g2/ and place in your Arduino's "Libraries" folder - OR - use the Arduino IDE's "Manage Libraries..." menu selection and enter "U8g2" in the search box.

* You can download the Ephemeris from https://github.com/hjd1964/ephemeris/ and place in your Arduino's "Libraries" folder.

In the Arduino IDE, from the "Tools, Boards" menu, pick the Teensy3.2 and 72MHz, or ESP32 Dev Module.

Select the device's USB serial port.

Finally, once the above steps are done, upload to the board.

Enable OnStep's ST4 hand control support (if you haven't already done so)

In OnStep's Config.xxx.h file you need to make sure the ST4 port is enabled #define ST4_ON or #define ST4_PULLUP, and that the hand control support is enabled too with #define ST4_HAND_CONTROL_ON

Power

The SHC device is powered across the ST4 port wiring.  On my MaxPCB, MiniPCB, etc. there's a shunt that can be installed to put +5V on Pin 1 of the RJ12 jack.  If you choose to enable this be sure to confirm that this (and the design in general) is compatible with any other device (CCD Camera, etc.) you intend to plug into the OnStep ST4 port.

Starting Up

When the SHC is powered up a "Teen Astro" splash screen will appear for a few seconds then it'll go dark.  At this point the SHC presents a signal to OnStep on it's ST4 port to indicate that a SHC is present.  After a couple of seconds OnStep reconfigures the ST4 port lines for synchronous serial comms and the SHC will start displaying the RA, Dec, and status information.

Use

While the menus' will help guide you through the selections it's good to know how the keys function.  At the center is the s[H]ift key, at the bottom are the [F] [f]eature keys.

        [N]

    [E] [H] [W]

        [S]

    [F]     [F]

  • Simply pressing [N],[S],[E],[W] guides in that direction.
  • A click on [H] cycles through the display of RA/Dec, Alt/Az, and Time.
  • A double click on [H] brings up feature key selection menu (guide rate, reticle light, utility light, focuser, rotator.)
    • Pressing the [F] or [f] keys then adjusts the feature selection (guide rate faster/slower, light brighter/dimmer, focus in/out, rotate left/right, etc.)
  • A long press on [H] brings up the menus
    • The [N],[S] keys then move up/down the menu selections.
    • The [W] key selects a menu item.
    • The [E] key navigates back to the prior level.

* = Instead of using the ST4 port connection it should be possible to use a standard serial interface (5V or 3.3V level TTL) to connect the SHC to OnStep though I've never tried it.  You'll need four lines run to OnStep: +5V, ground, TX, and RX (with RX connected to OnStep's TX and TX connected to OnStep's RX.)  The pins for RX3 and TX3 are identified on the EasyEDA SHC PCB silkscreen.

The same ST4SmartConfig.h file would be used to configure this with the following lines changed:

#define Ser Serial3
#define SERIAL_BAUD_DEFAULT 9600
